observables. As an application, we use two existing strong lens systems, B1608+656 ({zL}=0.6304) and {RXJ}1131-1231
({zL}=0.295), to show that the uncertainty in the inferred angular diameter distances is dominated by that in the velocity
dispersion, σ2, and its anisotropy. We find that the
current data on these systems should yield about 16\% uncertainty in {DA} per object. This improves to 13\% when we measure
σ2 at the so-called sweet-spot radius. Achieving 7\% is possible if we can determine σ2 with 5\% precision.},
