	abstract = {We present the discovery and measurements of a gravitationally lensed supernova ({SN}) behind the galaxy cluster {MOO} J1014+0038. Based on multi-band Hubble Space Telescope and Very Large Telescope ({VLT}) photometry of the supernova, and {VLT} spectroscopy of the host galaxy, we find a 97.5\% probability that this {SN} is a {SN} Ia, and a 2.5\% chance of a {CC} {SN}. Our typing algorithm combines the shape and color of the light curve with the expected rates of each {SN} type in the host galaxy. With a redshift of 2.2216, this is the highest redshift {SN} Ia discovered with a spectroscopic host-galaxy redshift. A further distinguishing feature is that the lensing cluster, at redshift 1.23, is the most distant to date to have an amplified {SN}. The {SN} lies in the middle of the color and light-curve shape distributions found at lower redshift, disfavoring strong evolution to z = 2.22. We estimate an amplification due to gravitational lensing of \{2.8\}{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}-0.5{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}+0.6{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} (1.10 ± 0.23 mag)—compatible with the value estimated from the weak-lensing-derived mass and the mass-concentration relation from Λ{CDM} simulations—making it the most amplified {SN} Ia discovered behind a galaxy cluster.},
