	abstract = {We present the {WFC}3 Infrared Spectroscopic Parallel ({WISP}) Survey. {WISP} is obtaining slitless, near-infrared grism spectroscopy of {\textasciitilde}90 independent, high-latitude fields by observing in the pure-parallel mode with the Wide Field Camera Three on the Hubble Space Telescope for a total of {\textasciitilde}250 orbits. Spectra are obtained with the G {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}102{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} (λ = 0.8-1.17 μm, R {\textasciitilde}210) and G {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}141{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} grisms (λ = 1.11-1.67 μm, R {\textasciitilde}130), together with direct imaging in the J and H bands (F110W and F140W, respectively). In the present paper, we present the first results from 19 {WISP} fields, covering approximately 63 arcmin{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}2{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}. For typical exposure times ({\textasciitilde}6400 s in G {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}102{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} and {\textasciitilde}2700 s in G {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}141{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}), we reach 5σ detection limits for emission lines of f {\textasciitilde} 5 × 10{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-17{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} erg s{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} cm{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-2{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} for compact objects. Typical direct imaging 5σ limits are 26.3 and 26.1 mag. ({AB}) in F110W and F140W, respectively. Restricting ourselves to the lines measured with the highest confidence, we present a list of 328 emission lines, in 229 objects, in a redshift range 0.3 \&lt; z \&lt; 3. The single-line emitters are likely to be a mix of Hα and [O {III}]5007,4959 Å, with Hα predominating. The overall surface density of high-confidence emission-line objects in our sample is approximately 4 per arcmin{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}2{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}. These first fields show high equivalent width sources, active galactic nucleus, and post-starburst galaxies. The median observed star formation rate ({SFR}) of our Hα-selected sample is 4 M {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}sun{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} yr{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}. At intermediate redshifts, we detect emission lines in galaxies as faint as H {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}140{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} {\textasciitilde} 25, or M{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}R{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} \&lt; -19, and are sensitive to {SFRs} down to less than 1 M {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}sun{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} yr{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}. The slitless grisms on {WFC}3 provide a unique opportunity to study the spectral properties of galaxies much fainter than L* at the peak of the galaxy assembly epoch. Based on observations made with the {NASA}/{ESA} Hubble Space Telescope, which is operated by the Association of Universities for Research in Astronomy, Inc., under {NASA} contract {NAS} 5-26555. These observations are associated with program 11696.},
