	doi = {10.1093/mnras/stu278},
	abstract = {I reanalyse the Riess et al. (hereafter R11) Cepheid data using the revised geometric maser distance to {NGC} 4258 of Humphreys et al. (hereafter H13). I explore different outlier rejection criteria designed to give a reduced χ{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}2{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} of unity and compare the results with the R11 rejection algorithm, which produces a reduced χ{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}2{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} that is substantially less than unity and, in some cases, leads to underestimates of the errors on parameters. I show that there are sub-luminous low-metallicity Cepheids in the R11 sample that skew the global fits of the period-luminosity relation. This has a small but non-negligible impact on the global fits using {NGC} 4258 as a distance scale anchor, but adds a poorly constrained source of systematic error when using the Large Magellanic Cloud as an anchor. I also show that the small Milky Way Cepheid sample with accurate parallax measurements leads to a distance to {NGC} 4258 that is in tension with the maser distance. I conclude that H{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}0{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} based on the {NGC} 4258 maser distance is H{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}0{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} = 70.6 ± 3.3 km s{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} Mpc{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}, compatible within 1σ with the recent determination from Planck for the base six-parameter Λ cold dark matter cosmology. If the H-band period-luminosity relation is assumed to be independent of metallicity and the three distance anchors are combined, I find H{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}0{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} = 72.5 ± 2.5 km s{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} Mpc{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}, which differs by 1.9σ from the Planck value. The differences between the Planck results and these estimates of H{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}0{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} are not large enough to provide compelling evidence for new physics at this stage.},
