	abstract = {We present Hubble Space Telescope images and 2 years of optical photometry of the quadruple quasar {HE} 0435-1223. The time delays between the intrinsic quasar variations are ∆t{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}{AD}{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}=-14.37{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}+0.75{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}-0.85{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}, ∆t{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}{AB}{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}=-8.00{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}+0.73{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}-0.82{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}, and ∆t{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}{AC}{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}=-2.10{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}+0.78{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}-0.71{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} days. We also observed nonintrinsic variations of {\textasciitilde}0.1 mag yr{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} that we attribute to microlensing. Instead of the traditional approach of assuming a rotation curve for the lens galaxy and then deriving the Hubble constant (H{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}0{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}), we assume H{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}0{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}=(72+/-7) km s{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} Mpc{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} and derive constraints on the rotation curve. On the scale over which the lensed images occur (1.2"=5 h{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} kpc{\textasciitilde}=1.5R{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}e{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}), the lens galaxy must have a rising rotation curve, and it cannot have a constant mass-to-light ratio. These results add to the evidence that the structures of early-type galaxies are heterogeneous. Based on observations obtained with the 1.3 m telescope of the Small and Moderate Aperture Research Telescope System ({SMARTS}), which is operated by the {SMARTS} Consortium; the Apache Point Observatory 3.5 m telescope, which is owned and operated by the Astrophysical Research Consortium; and the {NASA}/{ESA} Hubble Space Telescope as part of program {HST}-{GO}-9744 of the Space Telescope Science Institute, which is operated by the Association of Universities for Research in Astronomy, Inc., under {NASA} contract {NAS} 5-26555.},
