	abstract = {We present the Pan-{STARRS}1 discovery of {PS}1-10afx, a unique hydrogen-deficient superluminous supernova ({SLSN}) at redshift z = 1.388. The light curve peaked at z {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}P1{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} = 21.7 mag, making {PS}1-10afx comparable to the most luminous known {SNe}, with M{\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}u{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} = -22.3 mag. Our extensive optical and near-infrared observations indicate that the bolometric light curve of {PS}1-10afx rose on the unusually fast timescale of {\textasciitilde}12 days to the extraordinary peak luminosity of 4.1 × 10{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}44{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} erg s{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} (M {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}bol{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} = -22.8 mag) and subsequently faded rapidly. Equally important, the spectral energy distribution is unusually red for an {SLSN}, with a color temperature of {\textasciitilde}6800 K near maximum light, in contrast to previous hydrogen-poor {SLSNe}, which are bright in the ultraviolet ({UV}). The spectra more closely resemble those of a normal {SN} Ic than any known {SLSN}, with a photospheric velocity of {\textasciitilde}11, 000 km s{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} and evidence for line blanketing in the rest-frame {UV}. Despite the fast rise, these parameters imply a very large emitting radius (gsim 5 × 10{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}15{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} cm). We demonstrate that no existing theoretical model can satisfactorily explain this combination of properties: (1) a nickel-powered light curve cannot match the combination of high peak luminosity with the fast timescale; (2) models powered by the spindown energy of a rapidly rotating magnetar predict significantly hotter and faster ejecta; and (3) models invoking shock breakout through a dense circumstellar medium cannot explain the observed spectra or color evolution. The host galaxy is well detected in pre-explosion imaging with a luminosity near L*, a star formation rate of {\textasciitilde}15 M {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}☉{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater} yr{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}-1{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater}, and is fairly massive ({\textasciitilde}2 × 10{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}10{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} M {\textless}{SUB}{\textgreater}☉{\textless}/{SUB}{\textgreater}), with a stellar population age of {\textasciitilde}10{\textless}{SUP}{\textgreater}8{\textless}/{SUP}{\textgreater} yr, also in contrast to the young dwarf hosts of known hydrogen-poor {SLSNe}. {PS}1-10afx is distinct from known examples of {SLSNe} in its spectra, colors, light-curve shape, and host galaxy properties, suggesting that it resulted from a different channel than other hydrogen-poor {SLSNe}.},
